⚒️ The C.R.A.F.T. Framework

Lesson 3 - Structuring Effective Genealogical Prompts

Goal: Learn the C.R.A.F.T. framework and write improved prompts for genealogical research
Duration: 20-25 minutes
Prerequisites: Completion of Lessons 1 & 2
What You'll Learn: How to structure prompts using Context, Role, Action, Format, and Thoroughness

Why Structure Matters in Genealogical Prompts

Just as genealogical research benefits from systematic approaches, crafting effective AI prompts requires structure. The C.R.A.F.T. framework brings together essential elements from various prompt engineering strategies, specifically adapted for genealogical research needs.



Structured prompts help AI tools understand exactly what you need and provide more targeted, useful responses for your family history research. Think of C.R.A.F.T. as creating a clear research brief for your AI assistant.

Understanding the C.R.A.F.T. Framework

📋Context

What: Provide all relevant background information you already know

Why: The more details you provide (names, dates, locations, family connections, conflicting information, research gaps), the better equipped the AI will be to help you

Tip: Don't worry about giving too much information; AI tools can handle extensive context

👨‍🔬Role

What: Tell the AI what "persona" or "expert" role you want it to play

Why: This helps the AI understand the perspective from which it should analyze information and form responses

Examples: "Expert genealogist with 20+ years experience," "Census data specialist," "Immigration historian"

🎯Action

What: Clearly state what you want the AI to do

Why: Be precise about the output you're seeking to avoid generic responses

Examples: "Create a research plan," "Extract names from this newspaper," "Transcribe this baptismal record"

📊Format

What: Specify how you want the information organized or presented

Why: This makes the result easier to use and understand for your research

Examples: "Table format," "Bullet points," "Step-by-step list," "Timeline format"

⚖️Thoroughness

What: Add boundaries or specific details to prevent the AI from making assumptions

Why: Prevents the AI from making up information or straying from your intent

Examples: "Use only information provided," "Do not guess," "Limit to three paragraphs," "Focus on online resources only"

C.R.A.F.T. in Action: Before and After

Let's see how the C.R.A.F.T. framework transforms a vague prompt into a powerful research tool:

❌ Before: Vague Prompt

"Help me with my ancestor, John."


Problems:

  • No specific context provided
  • Unclear what type of help needed
  • No guidance on expertise level
  • No format preferences
  • No boundaries set

✅ After: C.R.A.F.T. Enhanced

Context: "I'm researching my great-grandfather, John Smith, born around 1880 in Ireland, immigrated to U.S. around 1900, settled in Boston, worked as a laborer. Limited immigration information."

Role: "Act as an expert genealogist specializing in 20th-century Irish immigration to the U.S."

Action: "Create a research plan to investigate his immigration path and naturalization records."

Format: "Provide as a step-by-step list with bullet points."

Thoroughness: "Suggest only online resources useful for beginner researchers."

C.R.A.F.T. Examples for Common Genealogy Tasks

Research Task C.R.A.F.T. Elements Example Prompt
Document Analysis C: Document details
R: Document expert
A: Interpret/transcribe
F: Table format
T: Only visible text 		"I have a 1890 death certificate for Mary O'Brien from Chicago. The handwriting is partially illegible. You are an expert in interpreting 19th-century vital records. Please transcribe all readable information and organize it in a table format with columns for Field Name and Transcribed Information. Only transcribe text that is clearly visible - mark unclear sections as [illegible]."
Research Strategy C: Current knowledge
R: Research strategist
A: Create plan
F: Step-by-step list
T: Online resources only 		"I'm stuck tracing Thomas Wilson who appears in 1880 census in Ohio but vanishes afterward. You are an expert genealogy research strategist. Create a comprehensive research plan to locate missing ancestors after 1880. Present as a numbered, step-by-step action plan. Focus only on online resources accessible to amateur researchers."

🔑 Key Takeaways

  • C.R.A.F.T. provides structure that transforms vague questions into powerful research tools
  • Context is crucial - provide all relevant background information for better AI responses
  • Role-playing helps - telling AI to act as a specific type of expert improves response quality
  • Clear actions get results - be specific about what you want the AI to do
  • Format matters - specify how you want information organized for easier use
  • Set boundaries - use thoroughness guidelines to prevent AI from making assumptions
